2) If the correct quantity (according to Deposco) is entered, the task in CycleCountQueue will be changed to "Completed" status. Test Case - Inventory Managemen.Unnamed: 3: Scan or enter starting location (any location in the warehouse) and hit enter
User will be directed to the nearest location that has a cycle count task waiting to be executed
User will scan the location they're directed to
User will be shown a list box with items in location needing to be cycle counted.
User will scan SKU and hit enter
On the next screen, user will select the pack type and enter the quantity they counted.

If they enter the quantity that Deposco thinks is in the system, they'll be returned to the previous screen with the list of items to be counted. If they enter a different quantity, they will be asked to re-count and re-enter since a variance was detected.
User will be asked to re-count as many times as necessary until they either enter the same quantity twice in a row, or enter the quantity Deposco believes is in the system.
User will be returned to the item listbox screen to select another item at that location if necessary.  If not, they can select "Next Location" and repeat the process if there are more tasks
User (typically a supervisor or manager) will enter the "Approve Variances" UI through a laptop or desktop
Test Case - Inventory Managemen.Unnamed: 4:
Depending on which action was taken, stock units will be updated to reflect what was counted, remain the same and cycle count task will be complete, or remain the same but generate a new cycle count task for the same location. 

The process will be repeated until either there is no variance detected, or the variance is accepted in "manage cycle count variances".
Test Case - Inventory Managemen.Unnamed: 5: Able to accept variance for ID 20

Test Case - Inventory Managemen.Unnamed: 3: A list of variances will be displayed.  A variance is any time a qty is entered that differs from what Deposco has listed in the system.
For each record you will see the item, counted qty, variance qty, reason code, and other relevant data. The columns listed can be adjusted.

Whoever is managing the variances can select the tasks and accept (stock units for that item/location will be updated based on what was counted), reject (stock unit for that location/item will remain with the same qty they had before the cycle count), or re-count (no change is made to the stock unit yet, and cycle count task is sent back to the floor to be re-counted).
User will select "Perform On Demand Location Cycle Count" from Inventory menu
Test Case - Inventory Managemen.Unnamed: 4:

Note: Be sure to delete and clear all entries in the CycleCountQueue, located within the Inventroy Admin tab BEOFRE TESTING.

Integration.Unnamed: 1: RTV Picking - Exceptions (no stock, damaged, etc.)
Integration.Unnamed: 4: User goes to location as directed by the handheld and finds that there is either no stock available to pick,  or stock is damaged.
Integration.Unnamed: 5: If there are no other locations with sufficient stock to fulfull that order, then that order and any other order on the same wave will go to back ordered status. The stock unit for that item/location combo will go on hold since the assumption is that it could not be picked from.

Integration.Unnamed: 4: User can select "exception" button
User will be prompted to give a reason (stock missing, stock damaged)
Select "exception" again from that screen after selecting a reason
If there is stock for that item in another location, User will be directed to fulfill that same order from a the other location where that stock exists
If no other stock exists for that item, it will go to back ordered status.
User goes to location as directed by the handheld and needs to suspend the picking task for whatever reason
Integration.Unnamed: 5:
1) When user selects "Suspend task", picking task state will update to "Suspend"
2) When a picking task is supsended, user is automatically prompted to complete the next picking task 
3) After the remaining pick tasks for the work group are complete, user is prompted again to pick the item that was skipped.

1) User is returned to MainMenu
2) The status of the work group for the pick wave changes to Suspended, and user is unassigned from the Workgroup
3) User can start the picking process again to continue the picking task if they decide to do so 
4) When picking is complete, Orderheader and Workgroup status will then be updated to "Complete"
